{"id":"2201.04824","submitter":"Shenglong Hu","authors":"Ke Ye and Shenglong Hu","title":"When geometry meets optimization theory: partially orthogonal tensors","comments":"60 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC cs.NA math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Due to the multi-linearity of tensors, most algorithms for tensor\noptimization problems are designed based on the block coordinate descent\nmethod. Such algorithms are widely employed by practitioners for their\nimplementability and effectiveness. However, these algorithms usually suffer\nfrom the lack of theoretical guarantee of global convergence and analysis of\nconvergence rate. In this paper, we propose a block coordinate descent type\nalgorithm for the low rank partially orthogonal tensor approximation problem\nand analyse its convergence behaviour. To achieve this, we carefully\ninvestigate the variety of low rank partially orthogonal tensors and its\ngeometric properties related to the parameter space, which enable us to locate\nKKT points of the concerned optimization problem. With the aid of these\ngeometric properties, we prove without any assumption that: (1) Our algorithm\nconverges globally to a KKT point; (2) For any given tensor, the algorithm\nexhibits an overall sublinear convergence with an explicit rate which is\nsharper than the usual $O(1/k)$ for first order methods in nonconvex\noptimization; {(3)} For a generic tensor, our algorithm converges $R$-linearly.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Jan 2022 07:51:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-01-14"}
